commit.message:
Add genres to TAG_INCLUDES

Genres were introduced in MusicBrainz a few months ago:
https://blog.metabrainz.org/2018/11/02/musicbrainz-introducing-genres/

One thing to note in that post:
> For now genres are exactly the same as (folksonomy) tags behind the scenes

An implication of this is that the new `genres` and `user-genres` are
applicable for all the cases where `tags` and `user-tags` are. Thus it
seemed like the "path of least resistance" to simply add these to the
potential include parameters for tags.

See also my question (and its answer(s)) on IRC:
https://chatlogs.metabrainz.org/brainzbot/metabrainz/msg/4336139/

Signed-off-by: Frederik Freso S. Olesen <freso.dk@gmail.com>

Specify supported version(s) of Python in setup.py

This specifies which versions of Python the library is compatible with.
This both prevents the module from being installed in an incompatible
Python environment, and will also enable users after future releases to
still `pip install musicbrainzngs` and get a version that is compatible
with their Python setup.

Versions are based on the ones currently being tested for in Travis
according to `.travis.yml`.

See https://packaging.python.org/guides/distributing-packages-using-setuptools/#python-requires
and https://packaging.python.org/guides/dropping-older-python-versions/

Signed-off-by: Frederik Freso S. Olesen <freso.dk@gmail.com>

Specify supported version(s) of Python in setup.py

This specifies which versions of Python the library is compatible with.
This both prevents the module from being installed in an incompatible
Python environment, and will also enable users after future releases to
still `pip install musicbrainzngs` and get a version that is compatible
with their Python setup.

Versions are based on the ones currently being tested for in Travis
according to `.travis.yml`.

See https://packaging.python.org/guides/distributing-packages-using-setuptools/#python-requires
and https://packaging.python.org/guides/dropping-older-python-versions/
